class KthLargest {
public:
    KthLargest(int k, vector<int>& nums) {
        this->k = k;
        for (int num : nums) {
            add(num);
        }
    }

    int add(int val) {
        if (minHeap.size() < k) {
            minHeap.push(val);
        } else if (val > minHeap.top()) {
            minHeap.pop();
            minHeap.push(val);
        }
        return minHeap.top();
    }
private:
    priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>> minHeap;
    int k;
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log k) for add
space complexity: O(k)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The provided solution utilizes a min-heap to efficiently track the kth largest element. The min-heap stores the k largest elements seen so far. When a new score is added, it is compared to the smallest element in the heap (the top). If the heap has less than k elements, the new score is added. If the heap has k elements and the new score is larger than the smallest element, the smallest element is replaced. This ensures the heap always contains the k largest scores. The kth largest score is simply the top of the heap.

